Relating this back to , when we plotted the vectors
\matrixOf{\uvec{v}}{B} \amp = \inv{P}\uvec{v}, \amp B \matrixOf{\uvec{v}}{B} \amp = B\inv{P}\uvec{v}
on their own set of wz-axes, we observed that the simple diagonal form of B made it easy to determine how \matrixOf{\uvec{v}}{B} is transformed by B: a stretch by a factor of 4 in the w-direction and both a reflection and a stretch by a factor of 2 in the z-direction. After superimposing a set of wz-axes onto the xy-axes using the \basisfont{B} vectors, we observed that \uvec{v} was transformed by A in exactly the same way relative to the new superimposed axes. This should not have been a surprise, since the formula A \uvec{v} = P B \inv{P} \uvec{v} = \ucobmtrx{B}{S} B \ucobmtrx{S}{B} \uvec{v} (where A = P B \inv{P} by the reversal of the similarity relation \inv{P} A P = B ) can be translated as:
